"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by the University of Edinburgh (WSC046)&#xa0;Summary of key points\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe University of Edinburgh\n \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nRelevant data\n&#xa0;&#xa0;Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhen women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat should universities and the higher education sector do to retain woman graduates and PhD students in academic caree\nrs? Are there examples of good practice?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nConclusion\n&#xa0;\nThe Unive\nrsity of Edinburgh welcomes the S\ncience and Technology Committee’s inquiry into Women in STEM careers and welcomes this opportunity to comment.\n&#xa0;\nReferences\n&#xa0;\n Royal Society of Edinburgh; \nTapping all our Talents\n – Women in science, technology, engineering and mathematics:  a strategy for Scotland\n, April 2012:  \nhttp://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/advice-papers/inquiry/women_in_stem/tapping_talents.pdf\n \n League of European Research Universities; \nWomen, research and universities:  excellence without gender bias\n,\n July 2012: \nhttp://www.leru.org/files/publications/LERU_Paper_Women_universities_and_research.pdf\n \n \nCon\nc\nordat to Support the Career Development of Researchers – An agreement between the funders a\nnd employers of researchers in the UK\n, June 2008:  \nhttp://www.vitae.ac.uk/policy-practice/505181/Concordat-to-Support-the-Career-Deve\nlopment-of-Researchers.html\n \n C. A. Moss-Racusin \net al.\n, \nScience Faculty’s subtle gender biases favor\n \nmale students\n; \nProceedings of the National Academy o\nf Sciences of the United States,\n 2012\n \nhttp://www.pnas.org/content/early/2012/09/14/1211286109.full.pdf+html\n   \n Wenneras, Christine and Wold, Agnes; \nNepotism and Sexism in Peer-Review\n, Nature 387 (22 May 199\n7), pp 341-343\n Cecha, E; Rubineaub, B; Sibeyc, S and Serond, C; P\nrofessional Role Confidence and Gendered Persistence in Engineering\n; American Sociological Review October 2011 vol. 76 no.5 641-666:  \nht\ntp://asr.sagepub.com/content/76/5/641\n \n \nFaulkener, Wendy; \nGenders in/of Engineering – A research report\n; University of Edinburgh/ESRC 2006: \nhtt\np://www.aog.ed.ac.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/4862/FaulknerGendersinEngineeringreport.pdf\n  \n&#xa0;\nSeptember 2013\n"